          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build and cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the {{tinned-tomatoes}}, {{tomato-puree}}, {{onion}}, {{garlic}}, {{smoked-paprika}}, {{light-brown-sugar}}, {{worcestershire-sauce}}, {{cider-vinegar}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}} to the slow cooker and stir to combine. Add the {{chicken-thighs-boneless}} and push them into the sauce. Cook on low for 6 hours, until the chicken is very tender. Using two forks, pull the chicken apart directly in the pot and stir through the sauce. Taste and adjust seasoning, add more cider vinegar for sharpness or more sugar for sweetness.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add more cider vinegar a teaspoon at a time until balanced. BBQ sauce should have a clear sweet-sour balance",
              "cause": "Brown sugar too high, or reduced significantly",
              "symptom": "Sauce too sweet and jammy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid and cook on high for 20 minutes to reduce. Alternatively, lift the pulled chicken out and reduce the sauce separately in a pan",
              "cause": "Chicken released a lot of liquid",
              "symptom": "Sauce watery rather than thick"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add another teaspoon of smoked paprika and stir. Taste before adding more",
              "cause": "Smoked paprika quantity too low",
              "symptom": "Lacks smokiness"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "BBQ pulled chicken is a weeknight crowd-pleaser. Serve in toasted brioche buns with coleslaw and pickles, or over rice with corn. The pulled chicken keeps in the fridge for three days and reheats well with a splash of water in a covered pan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
